VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'any pose Laura\'s in series. Now, let\'s go back to the main workflow. To make sure the background of the first image won\'t change, we have the SAM 3 node. As you should know, SAM 3 is now natively supported by ComfyUI, so we can use SAM'

[04:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '3 to extract only the pose. And then, we will send that extracted image to Kuan Image Edit 2511. Depending on your second image, you may need to change the prompt of SAM 3. Right now, I wrote the'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'woman. So, if I run the workflow, the woman will be extracted from the second image. For further modifications, enter into the subgraph. We also have this preview image node. So, instead of'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'running the whole workflow, just run the preview image node to see if the SAM 3 extraction was good. And here, we got the woman, so we are ready. Then, we have the Reactor Fast Face Swap node. Well, I found out that after Kuan Image'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Edit 2511 changes the pose, the person\'s face identity also changes. To fix that, we will be using Reactor. Unlike in the old days, the developer of Reactor has solved a lot of issues, making the node'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'easier to use than before. If you don\'t have the node, install the custom node pack called ComfyUI Reactor from the ComfyUI Manager. In this face swap node, I am using Hyper Swap as the swap model.'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The download links for the models I use in the Reactor nodes are available in this workflow. Some models are automatically downloaded when you use Reactor for the first time, but some models you need to manually download.'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, download the missing models and put them inside the correct folder of ComfyUI. Now, let\'s go back to the Reactor Fast Face Swap node. Here, I am using RetinaFace for face detection. Then, for the face restore model, I am'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using GPENBFR. It is important to use it because after the face swap, the result may look low-quality. With the restore model, we can fix that. Then we have the Reactor masking helper node for further refining'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the face swapping. In this node, I am using face YOLOv8 as the bbox model. Then for the SAM model, I am using SAM ViT B01. Depending on your swapping, you may need'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to play with the settings of this node. Well, I\'m going to skip that. Also, for further refinement, you can give your own mask to this node, and for that we can use the SAM 3 model. Then we have the save image node for saving'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outputs. We also have this face similarity Reactor node for checking how much the swapped face looks similar to the original. And we have another face similarity node for comparing the QN image edit output with the Reactor face'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'swap. Now, let\'s run the workflow and see how the result is going to look. So, it\'s finished. Let\'s have a look at it. Here is the result of the QN image edit pose change combined with Reactor. As'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can see, the result is quite good. Well, if it isn\'t good enough, we can always try another swap model. But in this case, I am pretty happy with it. Now, let\'s take a look at the'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'similarity. The Reactor face swap output has an 85% similarity with the face of the original image. Meanwhile, the QN image edit output similarity with the original image is around 62%. So, yeah, I think the Reactor output has'

[07:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much better similarity with the original face. Also, note that Reactor does have its limitations, especially in cases where hands or any other objects come over the face. In those cases, the swapping may not look good.'

